The Voice (U.S. TV series) - Wikipedia
The Voice is an American singing competition television series broadcast on NBC. It premiered during the spring television cycle on April 26, 2011. Based on the original The Voice of Holland, and part of The Voice franchise it has aired twelve seasons and aims to find currently unsigned singing talent (solo or duets, professional and amateur) contested by aspiring singers, age 13 or over, drawn from public auditions. Artists must be 13 or over to be considered, with at least four chairs turning around, that artist will be a member of one of the show's teams who is mentored and developed by one of its coaches. Each team is then developed by the coach to battle against another team in the live shows from a shortlist of finalists. Each season is driven by a single winner selected from the winning team being named as the winner of the competition in the final episode. The winner receives $100,000 and a recording contract with Universal Music Group.
The original series is presented by the creators of the format in the Netherlands, John de Mol and Roel van Velzen, in association with Talpa Productions and 25/7 Productions. The show was created by Talpa Productions, a subsidiary of Talpa Media Investments, and is currently produced by MGM Television and United Artists Media Group.
The Voice has received generally positive reviews from critics, with the third season receiving the highest praise from critics and the highest ratings. The Voice has received numerous awards and nominations, including six Primetime Emmy Award nominations, winning for Outstanding Reality-Competition Program in its second season.
